{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4922550f-80fe-40e8-b5ac-c8278e81b21a","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01P7ebpqzfPRwv5rYNS3Dsv6","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with TRX"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01VeJKcifBUbrhWePqTwRULN","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-f55840aa58d2478c806b4b5bbd946214 && dotnet test --report-trx 2>&1","description":"Run tests with TRX report","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run tests with TRX report"}],"interactionId":"0ba0f96c-6132-4d0c-8e2f-c56105735b7a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (via `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`). To produce a TRX report with `dotnet test`, you need to pass the appropriate reporter option.\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform and `dotnet test`, you can use:\n```\ndotnet test --report-trx\n```\n\nOr the older VSTest way:\n```\ndotnet test --logger trx\n```\n\nSince `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is set to true, the project is using the new testing platform. With the new testing platform integration, `dotnet test` in .NET 9 SDK should support `--report-trx` flag. But let me also check - the `--report-trx` flag requires the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package to be installed.\n \nMSTest 3.3 and later unified packages bundle TRX report support, so with MSTest 3.8.0, the `--report-trx` flag should work directly without needing a separate package installation.","outputTokens":526,"requestId":"CFC7:2E7D56:1465707:17A8D81:69EC132C"},"id":"dfb18c70-d2e1-4b6a-a06c-099cee208d08","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:04:54.770Z","parentId":"e071d6ef-d5a2-4d1b-aa04-9b7c7e14c1bd"}
